[[Image:BagdatesI290-280BCEPersia.jpg|thumb|Bagadates I (minted 290-280 BCE) wears the satrapal headdress, the ''kyrbasia'',<ref>Otto Mørkholm, ''Early Hellenistic Coinage: From the Accession of Alexander to the Peace of Apamea'' (Cambridge University Press) 1991:73f.</ref> with standing earflaps and a neck-guard<ref>John Curtis, Nigel Tallis and Béatrice André-Salvini, ''Forgotten Empire: The World of Ancient Persia'' 2005:258-9, fig. 454, Silver tetradrachm of Bagadates.</ref>]] '''Bagadates I''' ([[Koine Greek|Greek]]; from the [[Old Iranian]] ''Baga-dāta'', "Given by [the] god"),<ref>Since the Greek equivalent would be [[Theodore (name)|Theodore]], it will be easily understood that there were numerous individuals bearing this name; the name of one who appears briefly in [[Josephus]], ''Jewish War'' is discussed by Tal Ilan and Jonathan J. Price, "Seven Onomastic Problems in Josephus' 'Bellum Judaicum'", ''The Jewish Quarterly Review'' New Series '''84'''.2/3 (October 1993: 189-2) p 196f.</ref> also '''Bagdates''' or '''Baydad''' ([[Middle Persian]]), was a ''[[frataraka]]'' or [[Zoroastrianism|"Keeper of the Fire"]], and a governor or sub-dynast for the [[Seleucids]], ruling as a priest-king at [[Istakhr]] in the former [[Achaemenid]] heartland, the territory of [[Persis]] ([[Fars Province|Fars]]), after [[Alexander the Great]]'s conquests. He was the first indigenous Persian satrap to be appointed - or at least tolerated - by the Seleucids,<ref>[http://www.iranchamber.com/history/seleucids/seleucids.php (History of Iran) Jens Jacobson, "Seleucid Empire" 2004]</ref> who held the higher administrative posts tightly within the [[Ancient Macedonians|Greco-Macedonian]] circle that was headed by the "Companions" and their heirs.<ref>[[F. W. Walbank]], ''The Hellenistic World'' (Harvard University Press) 1981: "The Seleucids and the East", ''passim''.</ref> On the reverse of his coins, Bagadates is depicted standing in front of a Zoroastrian fire-altar, or seated in majesty holding a staff of authority and possibly a [[pomegranate]] in his left hand (''illustration, left''). Bagadates seems to have asserted his independence about 280 BCE, exploiting the turmoil after the death of [[Seleucus I]]. "That the first oriental reaction to [[Macedon]]ian rule should come from Persis, the homeland of the Achaemenids, is hardly surprising," Otto Mørkholm remarks.<ref>Mørkholm 1991:74.</ref>
The uprising against Seleucid control was continued by Bagadates' son, '''Oborzos''',<ref>The historian [[Polyaenus]] records a stratagem of Oborzos against Hellene colonists in Persis, noted by Mørkholm , ''op.cit.''.</ref> who emphasized the continuity by repeating the coinage type established by his father. However, some time during the 3rd century BCE the Seleucids terminated the pseudo-independence of Persis; during the 220s BCE, the satrap there was a Greek named Alexander, a brother of [[Molon]]. Persis finally drifted away from Seleucid control after the [[battle of Magnesia]] in 190 BCE. [[Image:Baydad.jpg|thumb|left|Another coin of Bagadates]] In a surviving inscription at [[Amyzon]] in [[Caria]], another '''Bagadates''' was appointed ''neokoros'' of the Temple of Artemis there in 321; it is surmised that his family had been potent landowners in the region before the conquests of Alexander.<ref>For instance, in Susan Sherwin-White and Amelie Kuhrt, ''From Samarkand to Sardis: A New Approach to the Seleucid Empire'' (London: Duckworth) 1993; see also P. Briant, "Les iraniens de l'Asie Mineure après la chute de l'empire achéménide", ''Dialogues de l'histoire ancienne'' '''11''' (1985:195).</ref> The son of this Bagadates, '''Ariaramnēs''',<ref>His name recalls [[Ariaramnes of Persia]], uncle of [[Cyrus the Great]].</ref> succeeded him as ''neokoros'' at Amyzon.
