{{About|the dharmic use of incense|plants mentioned in classical Hindu sources|Flora of the Indian epics period}} {{Infobox | title = Dhupa or incense stick offering | image = {{image array|perrow=2|height=80|width=120 | image1 = Devotee with Incense - Panchananda Mandir - Narna - Howrah 2014-04-14 0294.JPG | caption1=Hinduism, India | image2 = Incense stick and fa gao.jpg | caption2=Taoism, Singapore | image3 = Incense-LE.jpg | caption3=Buddhism, Cambodia | image4 = Thailand (272910785).jpg | caption4=Buddhism, Thailand }} }} '''Dhupa''' (धुप) is, in [[Indian religions]] (such as [[Hinduism]], [[Buddhism]], [[Jainism]], etc.), the ritual offering of [[Incense of India|incense]] during [[Puja (Hinduism)|puja]] to an image of a deity, or other object of veneration. It is also the [[Sanskrit]] word for incense or perfume itself.
[[Thai language|Thai]] language also borrows this word from Sanskrit to call [[joss sticks]] or [[incense sticks]], by omitting "a" in the word ''Dhupa''. So, the word retains the Sanskrit form when it is written in Thai alphabet as "Dhup" (ธูป). However, Sanskrit's Dh ({{IPA-sa|d̪ʱ|}}) is pronounced as aspirated T {{IPA-th|tʰ|}} in Thai, the word is normally pronounced or transliterated as "Thup" ({{IPA-th|tʰûːp|}})''. Incense burning before images, in temples and during prayer practice is also found in many parts of Asia, among followers of Jainism, Sikhism, Buddhism and Taoism.
The very idea of offering ''dhupa'' is personified in the [[dakini]] ''Dhupa'', who is said in the [[Bardo Thödol]] to appear on the third day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yoniversum.nl/dakini/dak8bodh.html|title=Eight Bodhisattva Dakinis}}</ref>
