{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2018}} {{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians --> | name = Propaganda | image = Propaganda2017MHT.jpg | caption = Propaganda performing at the [[Murray Hill Theatre]] in 2018. | image_size = | background = solo_singer | birth_name = Jason Emmanuel Petty | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1979|5|27}} | birth_place = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S. | genre = [[Christian hip hop]], [[spoken word]], [[underground hip hop]] | occupation = Rapper, pastor, poet | years_active = {{start date|2002}}–present | label = UpRok, Tunnel Rat, End of Earth, Humble Beast | associated_acts = [[Tunnel Rats (music group)|Tunnel Rats]], Footsoldiers, Odd Thomas, [[Beautiful Eulogy]], Lover of Rose Park Coffee Roasters | website = {{URL|humblebeast.com/propaganda/}} }}
'''Jason Emmanuel Petty ''' (born May 27, 1979), better known by his stage name '''Propaganda''', is an American [[Christian hip hop]] and [[spoken word]] artist and poet from [[Los Angeles]], California. He has released four albums as an independent artist and one collaborative album with the rapper Odd Thomas, and has performed and recorded as a member of the [[underground hip hop]] group [[Tunnel Rats (music group)|Tunnel Rats]] and associated act Footsoldiers.
==Biography and musical career== Petty was born Jason Emmanuel Petty on May 27, 1979 in [[Los Angeles]], California.<ref name="hhdb">{{cite web|url=http://www.hhhdb.com/index.php?id=426|title=Propaganda|publisher=The Holy Hip Hop DataBASE|accessdate=May 8, 2014}}</ref> In his very early childhood, his family moved into a violent, ethnically Mexican neighborhood.<ref name="path">{{cite web|last=Patrick|first=Kris|title=Propaganda, Shares Short Film Testimony on "Identity" on IamSecond|url=http://pathmegazine.com/news/gospel-rap/propaganda-shares-short-film-testimony-on-identity-on-iamsecond/|work=Path Magazine|publisher=Parallel Path Entertainment|accessdate=May 13, 2014|date=June 26, 2013}}</ref> As the only black child in the area, he was often teased due to his skin color. Later, his family moved again, this time to the suburbs, where his family was known as the "poor black family."<ref name="path" /> He learned to rap, and also took up dance, [[graffiti]], and formal drawing and painting.<ref name="uprock">{{cite web|title=Propaganda|url=http://www.toothandnail.com/media/4-Uprok%20Records/Propaganda/Pro-Bio.pdf|publisher=Uprok Records|accessdate=May 13, 2014}}</ref> Discovered by [[underground hip hop]] collective [[Tunnel Rats (music group)|Tunnel Rats]], he made his debut in 2002 on ''[[Speak Life]]'' by [[Sev Statik]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.crosswalk.com/11618786/|title = Out of Knowhere|date = June 1, 2003|accessdate = May 16, 2014|website = [[Crosswalk.com]]|publisher = [[Salem Web Network]]|last = Farias|first = Andree}}</ref> In 2003, Petty joined the Tunnel Rats, and on April 8, 2003, released his solo debut album with UpRok Records, entitled ''Out of Knowhere''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nibokun|first=Imade|title=Tunnel Rats: Controversial Christian Rap Collective Turns 20|url=http://www.laweekly.com/2013-10-24/music/tunnel-rats-dax-reynosa/|work=[[LA Weekly]]|publisher=[[Voice Media Group]]|accessdate=May 12, 2014|date=October 24, 2013}}</ref><ref name="jfh">{{cite web|last=Mabee|first=Justin|title=Propaganda, "Out of Nowhere" Review|url=http://www.jesusfreakhideout.com/cdreviews/OutOfKnowhere.asp|work=Jesus Freak Hideout|publisher=John DiBiase|accessdate=May 13, 2014|date=September 16, 2005}}</ref> In 2006 he released the ''I Am Not Them [[extended play|EP]]'' with Tunnel Rat Music and recorded ''Live This'' as part of Tunnel Rats-affiliated group Footsoldiers.<ref name="footsoldiers">{{Cite web|url = http://www.allmusic.com/artist/footsoldiers-mn0002326959/biography|title = Footsoldiers|date = |accessdate = May 13, 2013|website = [[AllMusic]]|publisher = [[All Media Network]]|last = Cordor|first = Cyril}}</ref> Footsoldiers also collaborated with [[KRS-One]] on his album ''[[Life (KRS-One album)|Life]]'', with Petty appearing on the song "I Ain't Leaving".<ref name="footsoldiers" /> Petty released a second solo EP, ''The Sketchbook: A Small Collection of Unreleased Material'', independently in 2008, and his second album, ''Listen Watch Focus'', also came out in 2008 through End of Earth Records.
Petty then released three albums through the [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]-based Humble Beast Records. The first, entitled ''Art Ambidextrous'', was recorded as a dual-album with Odd Thomas, and came out on February 1, 2011. Petty's next album, ''[[Excellent (album)|Excellent]]'', came out in 2012, and charted at No. 7 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' Top Gospel chart.<ref name="bbgos">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/1531307/propaganda/chart?f=323|title=Propaganda - Chart History: Gospel Albums|author=''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=May 8, 2014}}</ref> Petty's fourth solo album, ''[[Crimson Cord]]'', came out on April 29, 2014, and also charted successfully.<ref name="bb200">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/1531307/propaganda/chart?f=305|title=Propaganda - Chart History: ''Billboard'' 200|author=''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=May 8, 2014}}</ref> He dropped ''Crooked'', a project that asked serious political and social questions, on June 30, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/07/propaganda-crooked-album/|title=Propaganda Releases New Album ‘Crooked’ - XXL|website=XXL Mag|language=en|access-date=April 10, 2018}}</ref>
Propaganda has traveled the country on several tours, including the "Unlimited Up" tour<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.strangemusicinc.com/2016/05/20/murs-announces-unlimited-tour-propaganda|title=MURS Announces The ‘Unlimited Up’ Tour With Propaganda|work=Strange Music Inc.|access-date=April 10, 2018}}</ref> with [[Murs (rapper)|Murs]] and the "Spotlight" tour with [[Sho Baraka]] in 2016, as well as the "Tension Tour" with Kings Kaleidoscope in 2017.
==Other activities== In addition to his hip hop career, Jason Petty has worked as a youth pastor, led a poetry team called Selah, and helped his sister's dance ministry called "Live."<ref name="uprock" /> In 2013, he partnered with [[I Am Second]] in hosting a poetry contest, Spoken Word Challenge.<ref name="path" /><ref name="rapzilla spoken word">{{cite web|title=Propaganda Hosts Spoken Word Challenge|url=http://rapzilla.com/rz/news/1-press/6444-propaganda-hosts-spoken-word-challenge|work=[[Rapzilla]]|publisher=Philip Rood and Chad Horton|accessdate=May 13, 2014|date=June 20, 2012}}</ref> Beginning in 2017, Petty and his wife began The Red Couch Podcast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://humblebeast.com/news/red-couch-podcast-propaganda-alma/|title=The Red Couch Podcast with Propaganda & Alma - Humble Beast|publisher=|accessdate=June 22, 2017}}</ref>
