{{Hindu philosophy}}
'''Īśvarism''' is one of the religious streams in [[Hinduism]] along with other streams such as [[Brahmanism]], [[Jainism]], [[Buddhism]] and [[Lokayata]].<ref name="Congress1955">{{cite book|author=Indian History Congress|title=Proceedings, Indian History Congress|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fH9CAAAAYAAJ|year=1955|page=35}}</ref><ref name="Das1977">{{cite book|author=Dharmanarayan Das|title=The early history of Kaliṅga: a socio-economic and cultural history of coastal Orissa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZcgBAAAAMAAJ|year=1977|publisher=Punthi Pustak|page=67}}</ref>
==Īśvara==
In ancient texts of Indian philosophy, depending on the context, ''Īśvara'' can mean supreme soul, ruler, lord, king, queen  or husband. In medieval era Hindu texts, depending on the school of Hinduism, ''Īśvara'' means God, Supreme Being, personal god, or special [[Atman (Hinduism)|Self]]. [[Swami Vivekananda]] had opined that according to [[Vedas]], Īśvara is the supreme god and creator of the universe.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Complete Works of Swami Vivekananda - Volume 1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YCI-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT183|publisher=Advaita Ashrama (Publication House of Ramakrishna Math, Belur Math)|isbn=978-81-7505-862-0|pages=183–}}</ref>

